, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dimmoch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire; see   Dimock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dimock","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire, named perhaps from a British word akin to Welsh <i>tymoch</i> ‘pigsty’, but more probably from a Celtic <i>din</i> ‘fort’ + <i>moch</i> ‘swine’. A family of the name <i>Dymoke</i> held the hereditary position of King's Champion for thirty-four generations, starting in the late 14th century when John <i>Dymoke</i> adopted the role following his marriage to Margaret de Ludlow."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas De Dimmoch I was born in 1195, in Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Nicholas I Dimick or Dimmoch, was 25 and his mother, wife Lady Nicolas Dimick  or Dymmock I x, was 22. He married wife Nicholas IV Of Gloucestershire, England Dimick or Dymoke before 1220, in Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1195–":"1195–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1203–1230":"1203–1230","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","1203":"1203","Bef 1220":"enne 1220","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","Of Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dymock Manor, Dymock, Forest of Dean district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1195–":"1195–Kuollut","1195–Male":"1195–Kuollut","1203–1230":"1203–1230","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","1203":"1203","Bef 1220":"ennen vuotta 1220","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","Of Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dymock Manor, Dymock, Forest of Dean district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuni